# Adapter Pattern Skill

## Purpose
Guide an AI agent through implementing adapters that translate between ports and external systems in Hexagonal Architecture.

## Sections to Generate

### When to Use This Skill
Implementing a repository against a specific database, integrating with an external HTTP API, building an HTTP/gRPC handler that calls an inbound port, or wiring a message consumer to a use case.

### Driving Adapters (Inbound)
- Translate external triggers (HTTP, CLI, message) into calls to inbound ports
- Validate input format, serialize/deserialize, map errors back to external response format
- Keep them thin: NO business logic; if you find logic creeping in, it belongs in a use case

### Driven Adapters (Outbound)
- Implement an outbound port against a specific technology
- Translate adapter-specific errors into domain errors before returning
- Handle technical concerns: retries, circuit breakers, connection pooling — never the use case's concern

### Composition Root Wiring
- Adapters are instantiated and injected at the composition root (e.g. `cmd/main.go`)
- The use case never instantiates adapters directly

### Testing Adapters
- **Driven adapters:** contract test against the port — same expected behaviors any implementation must satisfy
- **Driving adapters:** integration test against the wired-up core with stubbed outbound ports

### Anti-patterns to Avoid
- Embedding business logic in adapters
- Skipping the port and depending on the concrete adapter from the core
- Letting adapter-specific exceptions leak past the port boundary
- Implementing multiple ports in a single adapter (one adapter = one port, generally)

### Verification
A correct adapter: implements the port interface fully; can be replaced with a different adapter (e.g. Postgres → MongoDB) without changing the use case; passes the same contract test suite as alternative implementations.
